items.description:
Please check out my Ko-Fi page if you are interested in supporting me.

LoRA commissions open! -> Fiverr

This is a LoHa LoRA! You need the extension! Why? They do a lot better with multi-concepts.

Trigger words for V1.19:

<lora:sheathedSwordv119:0.8>(sheathed, sword)
I suggest also using "arms up" or "crossed arms" cus if you don't, the character most likely will be generated holding the sheathed sword.

Follow the steps in the Model Version notes to reproduce my images.

Sample images generated from Nothing model.

All negative embeds should be easy to find. and Prompts should be included in the sample images! Click the little icon in the bottom right to see it.

It was trained on 43 512x512 images scraped from the internet and 20 epochs using animefull_final.

Danbooru tags generated by Waifu Diffusion 1.4 Tagger and fine tuned for specific tags.

modelVersions.name: v2.20
modelVersions.description:
Generate using a weight of 0.6-1 like this: <lora:sheathedSwordv119:0.8>


How I archived my generations:

  1. txt2img: DPM++ SDE Karras with 20 steps,512x512(can go up to 768 for wide or tall), Restore faces on (using CodeFormer weight 1.0 in Settings), Hires-fix on, to 1024x1024 (double original size) with your preferred upscaler and Denoise 0.5, CFG 7. Then send to img2img!

  2. img2img: DPM++ SED Karras with 20 steps, Restore faces on (CodeFormer weight 1), rescale to 1536x1536, CFG 7, Denoise between 0.3-0.7 (based on how much you want to improve the image), SAME PROMPT! Send to extras when happy with img2img/inpaint results.

  3. extras: Scale to x3 (final will be 4608x4608, I suggest going lower, I did x3 just for the samples here) Upscaler 1 - FatalAnime 4x, Upscaler 2 - SwinIR 4x with 0.10 visibility, GFPGAN 0.10 visibility, CodeFormer 0.10 visibility.

items.name: Multi
items.description:
IF YOU ENJOY THE MODEL PLEASE RATE/REVIEW IT!!

I found that most models are to opinionated, hence the multi model. It excels at detailed prompts and doesn't try to turn everything into a human (but you still can generate the human's ofcourse).

For reference please check the images posted, for the first few I kept all the settings the same so to get the result all you have to do is copy the pos & neg prompt and you're done. The ones after that i just copied from other posts and posted the ones that came out. Thanks for those prompts.

I seem to run on coffee so if you want to keep me running, here is my coffee link (also taking custom requests in exchange for for a couple of double espressos, slide into dm): https://www.buymeacoffee.com/olliesd

recommended settings are:
DPM++ SDE
CLIP skip 1
for detailed prompts use high CFG.
Hires fix makes everything better!
no vea required

FYI if you're getting image collections instead of 1 images try tuning down the weights.


When prompting for people it'll tend to look like chilloutmix with some softer lighting. Although the same thing can easily be achieved by adding some shadow & skin related tags to your prompt.

This model is also surprisingly good at inpainting!

GLHF & IF YOU GENERATE ANY AWESOME IMAGES, SHARE THEM PLEASE :)

Maria Mizuse from Tomodachi Game


I hadn't noticed her hair and eye colors were different in half of the anime until I started working on this model. Haha!


Prompts:-

  • Trigger Word:
    maria_olis

  • Outfit 1:
    pink hair, hair ribbon, green eyes, neck ribbon, white shirt, black jacket, black skirt, garter straps, thighhighs

  • Outfit 2:
    brown hair, hairclip, blue eyes, black serafuku, red neckerchief, name tag, pleated skirt, black thighhighs

  • Extra:
    1girl, solo
    (please refer to my sample images)

Weight: 1 (you may experiment yourself)

All my models were trained with 512x512 pixels.
For optimal results, please upscale your generated outputs with your preferred methods.


My seventh model.

This time, I have decided to use the D-Adaptation optimizer, which can automatically choose a learning rate for me. In the past, I experimented with it but didn't like the results. However, my recent models were getting overcooked quite easily with the default learning rates. I also tried different learning rates but couldn't decide on the best ones. Therefore, I decided to give D-Adaptation another try.

I realized that I had wasted too much time on stuff I couldn't decide. Once again, I trained over 50 models for a single character. Perhaps I should just simplify my workflow, probably into three parts: preparing the dataset, training a few models with varying numbers of epochs using D-Adaptation, and finally choosing the "best" model by comparing the generations from the last epochs across multiple batches.

Btw, I noticed that I mistakenly disabled aspect ratio bucketing in my previous two models while experimenting with a batch size of 1. No wonder the models sometimes couldn't generate the character's face. Maybe I'll retrain them when I get bored.

Anyway. hopefully some of you will like this model.

items.name: Guide: How to prompt for beginners (anime)
items.description:
(I added all images from this post to .zip archive. Click download to see them in full resolution)

Everything I write here is about txt2img without img2img, hires.fix, inpaint and extensions like controlnet. Iâ€™m gonna focus on creating prompt, not how to make more detailed, upscaled or edited image. Everything was tested mostly on anime models so it may not work with realistic models.


Before we start Iâ€™d like to keep your attention to set up a few things if you havenâ€™t done it yet. This will help you get good images.

First of all you should set up VAE you will be using with your model. (If model has baked VAE you donâ€™t need to do anything). To do so download VAE file (if you havenâ€™t) and put it intoÂ  â€œstable-diffusion-webui\models\VAEâ€ folder. Go to settings->Stable Diffusion, in SD VAE click blue arrows and select your VAE. Click apply settings.

You can also go to Settings -> User Interface -> Quick settings List and add there sd_vae if you want to have this setting in your txt2img tab.

For all examples I was using this VAE: https://civitai.com/models/23906/kl-f8-anime2-vae

I highly recommend you using Negative embeddings. All examples in this post were made with EasyNegative embedding. No additional negative tags.

To use it, download and put it into â€œstable-diffusion-webui\embeddingsâ€ folder. Then add its file name to negative prompt. (I suggest you use EasyNegative which you can download from here: https://civitai.com/models/7808/easynegative, but you can use other embeddings)

I suggest you try Clip skip: 2. It should work better with anime models. Try both - 1 or 2, to find what you like more.

To add Clip skip add CLIP_stop_at_last_layers in Settings -> User Interface -> Quick settings List, click apply settings and you should have this option in txt2img tab.

____

You can find many prompts on the Internet or this site but I think you should not just copy them, at least not at the beginning. Better way is to look at them and try every tag separately.Â 

Itâ€™s important to know how a specific tag works because you will be creating compositions with it and adding random words to get result you want may be really frustrating. Sometimes tag is different from a normal word, so you can spend a lot of time trying to get it on your image which you could do with a simple tag.Â 

Weights in your tags.

By adding more weight to your tag (tag:1.x/1.1/1.5 etc.) you can force AI to add something to your image, but I highly recommend you start every new prompt without weights, because changing it will change your image. If you use many different weights in many tags, it may change your image into a complete mess which we donâ€™t want to. Sure, you can use it if AI is not giving you results you like but first see how image looks like on :1.0 and change this value only if you really have to. Be careful with this, set this value as low as possible (like (tag:1.1/ 1.2) not (tag:1.6/2), it concerns negative and positive prompt).

Personally, in many cases Iâ€™m actually decreasing weights rather than increasing them.

Example (prompt: 1girl in positive and EasyNegative in negative prompt):

How to write prompt?

In my opinion best way to start is using very simple prompt. Like:

P: 1girl

N: EasyNegative (this is negative embedding, if you are using other use their file name)

Then you can add tags to see how it will change your image.

Most anime models use Danbooru tags, so you can go to Danbooru site and search for tags you can use in your image. If you click â€œ?â€ in tag you want, you can read a short explanation of what it is and see in which situations itâ€™s used. If tag has _ in it use space instead, it should work better.

Basically, you need to be precise what you want in your image. If you want something that is too general AI may not be able to generate it. Depending on model you're using, you may get decent results but on some models you may end up with weird objects or deformed image. To prevent this you should add at least few informations about what is going on and what the characters (if you want to have them in your image) look like. Try to think what elements your image needs. If for example you want to have person outdoors you can add details like grass, leaves, trees, but also blue sky, flying butterflies to get more natural look.Â 

Donâ€™t add too many tags, if you do it may be harder to get result you want.

I would think about creating prompt in this way:Â 

[character description] + [actions the character performs] + [background] + [rest of your prompt]

Example:

1girl, blue eyes, black hair, long hair, upper body, school uniform, standing, hand up, facing viewer, classroom, chalkboard, kanji

or

1girl, white shirt, long sleeves, black jeans, backpack, full body, walking, landscape, mountain, night, from behind, snow

You may need tags for viewing angles and body position/movement to have more control of what is going on in your image. Of course clothes and background are important too but many models will add decent looking clothes even if you donâ€™t add them to your prompt. With background you can specify elements you want to have in your image, you donâ€™t need to write â€œtrees in the backgroundâ€¦â€, adding outdoors, trees, autumn will work instead. Be sure to specify background or it may give you weird results. If you donâ€™t have an idea for that you can add white background or indoors/outdoors.

Here is a list of tags that may help you:

  • dutch angle, from above, from below, from behind, from side, straight-on or facing viewer.

  • full body, cowboy shot, upper body, close-up.

  • standing, sitting (this one has many versions like wariza, crossed legs, sitting on object, etc. you can find them on danbooru), lying, jumping, running, walking, arched back, leaning forward, and so on.



If AI is giving you something you donâ€™t want on your image add it to negative prompt. Some things are obvious like: you are getting cat on your image so you can add cat to negative prompt to (hopefully) remove it. Other things may not be so obvious. For example: you want your character to be wearing a skirt and shirt but AI gives you some odd clothes. It may be a good idea to add dress to negative prompt. AI may be confused and merge shirt and skirt together.Â

items.name: ORIGAMI
items.description:
Origami is the Japanese art of folding paper into intricate and sculptural designs without the use of cutting or gluing.

The word "origami" comes from the Japanese words "ori" meaning "folding" and "kami" meaning "paper." This ancient art form has been practiced for centuries and is enjoyed by people of all ages around the world.

Origami involves creating various shapes, objects, and figures by folding a single sheet of paper. Traditional origami designs include animals, plants, geometric shapes, and decorative items.

The art of origami requires precision, patience, and an understanding of folding techniques. Origami artists use different folding methods, such as valley folds, mountain folds, and reverse folds, to create intricate patterns and achieve desired shapes.

Origami paper, known as "kami," is typically square and comes in a variety of colors and patterns. However, any type of paper can be used for origami, including newspaper, wrapping paper, or even dollar bills.

Origami not only serves as a creative outlet but also offers various benefits. It can improve concentration, develop problem-solving skills, and provide a sense of relaxation and mindfulness.

Today, origami has evolved beyond traditional designs, and contemporary artists and enthusiasts experiment with new techniques and innovative approaches. Advanced origami creations can be incredibly complex and visually stunning, showcasing the limitless possibilities of this art form.

Origami is not only a form of artistic expression but also a cultural symbol of patience, precision, and appreciation for the beauty of simplicity. It continues to captivate and inspire people worldwide, inviting them to explore the magical world of paper folding.

items.name: Lisa - Hentai University
items.description:
This is a LoRA for the character Lisa, from Hentai University a game by Noodle Jacuzzi.

Lisa's art is from the artist Oreteki18kin, the set -

Mama to Hame Chao!! Mama Man Cho! & Mama to Hame Chao!! Mama Man Cho! Natsu

I've been working my way through making these for all the characters currently in the game, and sharing them in the Discord for HU, but figured I should also put them up here.

In general, I'm working from pretty limited image sets, so expect the results to be a bit wonky at times.

I recommend a weight of around 0.5, possibly lower depending if you're combining the character LoRA with other styles/costumes/etc. along with tagging some defining characteristics of the character you're generating. Higher than that can really push the artist's original style, and may cause you issues.

All characters I train have a "character tag" added into the set to help generate them fairly reliably.

Recommended LoRA Weight - 0.5 for fairly flexible, higher if you want more of the original artist's style, lower if it doesn't play nice with other loras.

Character tag - HULisa
Recommended tags - black hair, ponytail, medium hair, glasses, large breasts, brown eyes,

I may have forgotten to check and tag eye color when doing my testing, but hey. If you want it to be "set accurate" be sure to tag.

I've got quite a backlog of these made up already, so I'll be uploading them on and off.

Check my other uploads as I put them out for more HU characters, and if you want any specific character put up soon, let me know.
